docs.lead_paragraph: The Pre-Existing Condition Insurance Plan will be extended through March so patients can continue treatment while they find other coverage, the Obama administration said.

headline.main: Program to Cover Major Illnesses Is Extended
headline.print_headline: Program to Cover Major Illnesses Is Extended

docs.abstract: Obama administration says Pre-Existing Condition Insurance Plan, special insurance program for people with cancer, heart disease and other serious illnesses, will be extended for two additional months so patients can continue treatment while they search for other coverage; about 30,000 people are currently in program, essentially a high-risk pool sponsored by the federal government.
docs.snippet: The Pre-Existing Condition Insurance Plan will be extended through March so patients can continue treatment while they find other coverage, the Obama administration said.

docs.lead_paragraph: A group financed in part by the Koch brothers is spending millions on ads aimed at vulnerable Democrats who supported the Affordable Care Act.

headline.main: Ads Attacking Health Law Stagger Outspent Democrats
headline.print_headline: Ads Attacking on Health Law Stagger Outspent Democrats

docs.abstract: Americans for Prosperity, group financed in part by billionaire Koch brothers, is spending millions on television ads aimed at vulnerable Senate and House Democrats who supported the Affordable Care Act; unusually aggressive early run of ads are making Democrats, many of whom lack resources to fight back in early stages of their midterm campaigns, increasingly anxious.

docs.lead_paragraph: The effort to extend long-term unemployment benefits suffered a setback in Washington when two separate proposals were voted down and the possibility of a bipartisan deal collapsed.

headline.main: Unemployment Extension Is Stalled, With 2 Proposals Defeated in the Senate
headline.print_headline: Unemployment Extension Is Stalled, With 2 Proposals Defeated in the Senate

docs.abstract: Unemployment benefits for 1.3 million of America's long-term unemployed, as well as millions more in future, are in jeopardy after Senate efforts to reach accord on legislation to revive benefits collapses in partisan finger-pointing.
docs.snippet: The effort to extend long-term unemployment benefits suffered a setback in Washington when two separate proposals were voted down and the possibility of a bipartisan deal collapsed.
